<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWS ROUNDUP: COUNTYWIDE; 
</P>
<P>
DISTRICT DECLARES WAR ON WATER WASTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GLENN BRIGGS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The board of Ventura County's largest water district declared war on the waste 
of the precious liquid Wednesday as the area enters its fourth year of drought. 
</P>
<P>
"We must save, save, save," said James A. Hubert, engineer-manager of the 
Calleguas Municipal Water District. 
</P>
<P>
Although current supplies will meet this year's needs, Hubert said, a 
continuing drought could cause a shortage of 3,000 to 4,000 acre-feet of water. 
</P>
<P>
Hubert said most home water waste comes from toilets, showers, watering lawns 
and washing cars. 
</P>
<P>
Calleguas directors voted to declare May "Water Awareness Month" and two weeks 
ago endorsed a call by the district's supplier, the Metropolitan Water 
District, for increased conservation efforts. 
</P>
<P>
Information on saving water is available from the Ventura County Water 
Conservation Office, (805) 654-2471 or 654-2440. GLENN BRIGGS 
</P>
</TEXT>
