<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: DIAMOND BAR; 
</P>
<P>
WATER CONSERVATION URGED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The City Council on Tuesday adopted a resolution asking residents to cut down 
on water usage by 10% to help offset a prolonged statewide drought. 
</P>
<P>
But the measure is only voluntary, at a time when some Southland water 
officials are urging counties and cities to adopt mandatory water conservation 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
The resolution lists ways to conserve, including not hosing down sidewalks and 
driveways, installing low-flow devices in toilets, adjusting sprinklers to 
avoid runoff, avoiding watering during the hot part of the day or during peak 
hours, shutting off fountains and repairing leaky faucets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
