<HEADLINE>
<P>
A DAY IN THE PARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KAREN KINGSBURY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lanark Recreation Center 
</P>
<P>
21816 Lanark St., Canoga Park 
</P>
<P>
Size: 19 acres 
</P>
<P>
Facilities: Lighted tennis courts, baseball diamonds, swimming pool, indoor 
gymnasium, picnic facilities, play area. 
</P>
<P>
Hours: 9 a.m. to 10 p.m. Monday through Friday; 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Saturday and 
Sunday 
</P>
<P>
Information: (818) 883-1503 
</P>
<P>
Before Ray Notaro came along, Lanark Recreation Center was just another city 
park. 
</P>
<P>
But in 1986, Notaro and Frankie Goodman started the Lanark Boxing Club and 
began organizing classes enabling area youngsters to learn how to box. Today, 
more than 300 children, some as young as 8, have participated in the boxing 
program. Safety gear is provided by the park and a nominal registration fee 
pays for a mouthpiece and hand wrappings. 
</P>
<P>
Lanark also is the only city park with a fencing program. Instructor Edwin 
Hurst offers night classes three times a week to the public. Both programs have 
helped bring more young people to the park, said park director John Perez Jr. 
"Lanark is a place of diversity where a child can get involved in the typical 
baseball, tennis or swimming," Perez said. And the atypical too. KAREN 
KINGSBURY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, boxing HYUNGWON KANG / For the Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Profile 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA040590-0172 </DOCNO>
